<div class="markdown"><h1 id="What-is-the-fastest-path-between-two-points?">What is the fastest path between two points?</h1><p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/live/zGiFiY2y5_U?si=fg7udrZ6dWFtbvNH &quot;Brachistochrone introduction - click to watch&quot;"><img alt="Brachistochrone introduction" src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/zGiFiY2y5_U/0.jpg"/></a></p><p>We want to design a track that minimizes the time it takes to descend from height, <span class="tex">\(h\)</span>, to height 0 and we want to travel forward by distance, <span class="tex">\(L\)</span>. </p><p>What shape should the track take?</p><p>total time is, <span class="tex">\(T\)</span>, </p><p class="tex">$$T = \int_0^L\frac{ds}{v}$$</p><p>For a first approximation, consider sliding without friction, </p><p class="tex">$$mgh = \frac{1}{2}mv^2 + mgf(x)$$</p><p>. </p><p>Our track can only have 1 height, <span class="tex">\(y\)</span> for every position, <span class="tex">\(x\)</span>, so </p><p class="tex">$$y(x) = f(x)$$</p><p>and </p><p class="tex">$$v = \sqrt{2g(h-f(x))}$$</p><p>, </p><p>and the distance traveled is <span class="tex">\(ds = \sqrt{dx^2+dy^2}= \sqrt{dx^2+dx^2\frac{df}{dx}^2}\)</span> or</p><p class="tex">$$ds = dx\sqrt{1+f'^2}$$</p><p>our total time, <span class="tex">\(T\)</span>, is now</p><p class="tex">$$T = \int_0^L\frac{ds}{v}=\int_0^L\sqrt{\frac{1+f'^2}{2g(h-f)}}dx$$</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
using Plots
using LaTeXStrings
end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>g = 9.81</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-g">9.81</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>F(f, df, h = 1) = ((1+df^2)/(2*g*(h-f))).^0.5</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-F">F (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function T(F, f, df, L = 1, dx=0.0001)
    x = range(dx, L, step = dx)
    val = F.(f.(x), df.(x)).*dx
    T = sum(val)
    return T
end</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-T">T (generic function with 3 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function build_parabola(p1, h=1, L=1)
    x1, y1 = p1
    A = [0 0 1; 
         x1^2 x1 x1^0;
         L^2 L L^0]
    b = [h, y1, 0]
    C = A\b
    f(x) = C[1]*x^2+C[2]*x+C[3]
    df(x) = 2*C[1]*x +C[2]
    return f, df
end</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-build_parabola">build_parabola (generic function with 3 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    y1s = range(0, 0.7, step=0.05)
    T_array = zeros(length(y1s))
    P = plot([0, 1], [1, 0], 
             markershape=:rect, 
             linetype=:scatter,
            label = "start-stop")
    dx = 0.0001
    x = range(dx, 1, step = dx)
    for (i, y1) in enumerate(y1s)
        f, df = build_parabola([0.5, y1])
        T_array[i] = T(F, f, df, 1, dx)
        plot!(P, x, f.(x), label = "y"*string(i))
    end
plot!(P, title = "Varying paths from start to stop",
     xlabel = "X-location (m)",
     ylabel = "Y-location (m)")
plot!(ones(length(y1s)).*0.5, 
      y1s, 
      markershape=:circ,
      linetype=:scatter,
     label = "fixed points")
    P
end</code></pre>
